The Finite Difference Method (FDM) is a numerical technique for solving differential equations by approximating derivatives with finite differences. For a partial differential equation (PDE) like the heat equation, ∂u/∂t = α(∂²u/∂x²), we discretize the domain in both time and space. Let u(x, t) be represented by uᵢʲ = u(xᵢ, tʲ), where xᵢ = iΔx and tʲ = jΔt.

The time derivative can be approximated using a forward difference:
∂u/∂t ≈ (uᵢʲ⁺¹ - uᵢʲ) / Δt

The second spatial derivative is approximated using a central difference:
∂²u/∂x² ≈ (uᵢ₊₁ʲ - 2uᵢʲ + uᵢ₋₁ʲ) / (Δx)²

Substituting these into the heat equation gives the Forward-Time Central-Space (FTCS) explicit scheme:
(uᵢʲ⁺¹ - uᵢʲ) / Δt = α * (uᵢ₊₁ʲ - 2uᵢʲ + uᵢ₋₁ʲ) / (Δx)²

Rearranging for uᵢʲ⁺¹ yields the update rule:
uᵢʲ⁺¹ = uᵢʲ + (αΔt / (Δx)²) * (uᵢ₊₁ʲ - 2uᵢʲ + uᵢ₋₁ʲ)

This scheme is explicit because the value at the new time step (j+1) can be calculated directly from values at the current time step (j). However, it is only conditionally stable, requiring the Courant-Friedrichs-Lewy (CFL) condition to be met for convergence: (αΔt / (Δx)²) ≤ 1/2.
